"We are heartbroken in the State of Florida, again. Just days after the massive shooting at the Fort Lauderdale Airport, we learned two of our members in uniform have lost their lives while protecting and serving the public. Making this even more painful, this tragedy occurred on Law Enforcement Appreciation Day. One of the police officers, a 17-year veteran with the Orlando Police Department and devoted mother, Master Sgt. Debra Clayton, was cowardly gunned down in broad daylight. As we tried to comprehend this unspeakable crime, Deputy First Class Normal Lewis died in a car accident as he joined the search for the suspect. We stand today together in support of our law enforcement family and we thank you for all your sacrifices and hard work. The loss of these exceptional law enforcement officers reminds us of the urgency to stand up against gun violence by pushing to pass stricter gun laws to make our communities safer in Florida and across our Nation". -Congressman Darren Soto

Congress of the United States House of Representatives Darren Soto 9th District, Florida   ***MEDIA ADVISORY*** Rep. Soto To Launch LGBTQ Study Group Soto calls for meeting to address Trump's latest attacks on the LGBTQ community       February 24, 2017   ORLANDO,FL.- Congressman Darren Soto will be hosting a strategic planning roundtable with policymakers, the American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU), and community organizers to discuss President Donald Trump‚Äôs latest attack on LGBTQ youth and the rumored executive order that would allow businesses to discriminate against the LGBT community.    The Trump administration announced this week the revocation of a federal policy under Title IX to prohibit schools from discriminating against transgender students. This is contrary to American values and Trump's own campaign‚Äôs promises.    Congressman Soto is holding this meeting to create a study group on the challenges faced by lesbian transgender, gay, bisexual and queer people in the 9th District, and to begin the process of creating an Advisory Council to advance his work in support of the LGBTQ community in the District. The study group will report back in 60 days.     WHAT: Congressman Darren Soto meeting with LGBTQ leaders and allies    WHO: Osceola Commissioner Cheryl Grieb, Heather Welkie and Brett Burlone from Zebra Coalition, Roxy Santiago and Tony Sandonato Human Rights Campaign, Terry DeCarlo LGBT Center, Christopher Cuevas Q Latin X, Elizabeth McCarthy LGBTA Democratic Caucus of Florida, ACLU Central Florida Board President Chardo Richardson and Temeka Hampton, Equality Florida Karen Castelloes, Orlando LGBT Chamber of Commerce Lisa Brown, Orange County DEC Chair, Wes Hodge, Projecto Somos Orlando Ricardo Negron, LGBTQ Alliance Brandi Fliegelman, among others.      WHEN: Friday, February 24, 2017   TIME: 3 p.m. to 4:30 p.m.   LOCATION: District Office, Kissimmee FL    Members of the media who would like to cover the event are encouraged to register izamontalvopressfl@gmail.com or iza.montalvo@mail.house.gov   Congressman Darren Soto represents Florida‚Äôs 9th Congressional District, which includes Osceola County, as well as parts of Orange and Polk counties.   www.soto.house.gov

Today we recognize the 100th Anniversary of the Jones-Shafroth Act conferring U.S. citizenship on the people of Puerto Rico.  During the last 100 years, Puerto Ricans have changed the course of American History. We served with distinction in our U.S. military including our heroic Borinqueneers who fought bravely in WWI, WWII, and the Korean War, and we continue to serve in the military in great numbers.   We have pioneering doctors like our first Hispanic and first female U.S. Surgeon General, Antonia Novello. Sports greats like Roberto Clemente, Ivan Rodr√≠guez, Bernie Williams and Jorge Posada have impressed the American people on the baseball field.  Science teacher Joe Acaba soared to new heights as an astronaut.    Entertainers such as Jennifer L√≥pez, Marc Anthony, Ricky Martin, Willie Col√≥n, Tito Nieves and Lin-Manuel Miranda have thrilled audiences across the world.  And of course, Sonia Sotomayor who now sits on the United States Supreme Court. These and many other Puerto Rican heroes have instilled amazing historic and cultural contributions throughout our nation including changing the face of major cities such as New York, Chicago, and Orlando.    This history has also been an emotional one.  To date, our brothers and sisters on the Island do not enjoy the same rights as we in the Diaspora. La Isla del Encanto is still experiencing a terrible depression. And we in the United States Congress must step up to help bring prosperity and equality to Puerto Rico.    I am honored to serve on the Subcommittees on Oversight and Insular Lands with jurisdiction to review major Puerto Rico issues related to PROMESA, federal lands, and status issues. I will continue to work with my fellow Members of Congress to reduce the Island‚Äôs debt, bring relief directly to Puerto Ricans living on the Island, and fight for new economic opportunities there.  I will also closely monitor the upcoming plebiscite and will respect the will of the people with regard to status.   Together we can forge a new century of leadership for all Puerto Ricans both in the Diaspora and on the Island!  Unidos y Pa‚Äôlante!

Statement about the passing of former Osceola County Chairman Frank Attkisson    April 7, 2017    WASHINGTON, D.C.-U.S. Representative Darren Soto released the following statement today about the sudden passing of former Osceola County Chairman Frank Attkisson. During his career in public service, Attkisson served in the Florida House of Representatives for 10 years and as the Mayor of Kissimmee.   ‚ÄúFrank was a friend to me, and to so many people in our community.  He was deeply committed to making life better and opportunity greater for all the people of Osceola County.  Today, our community mourns as one, and my wife Amanda and I send our deepest condolences to Frank's family. He will be greatly missed.‚Äù                            www.soto.gov

Securing and defending Americans are among my top priorities. Over the next 7 days, I want to share with you the amendments I made to strengthen the Make America Secure Appropriations Act (HR3219). This House-passed legislation funds Defense, Military Construction-VA, Energy and Water Development, and Legislative Branch. Follow along with #RepSotoDefenseApprops   Day 1: I introduced two amendments on the House Floor to increase total funding for prostate cancer research to $100 million and gulf war illness research to $21 million. A total increase of $11 million to the Defense Health Program!

In the appropriations minibus for FY18, I prioritized improving cancer research and treatment for all service members through partnerships between the Walter Reed Military Medical Center and the Murtha Cancer Center; a collaboration that will benefit the Moffitt Cancer Center in Florida! I also secured $182 million for the High-Performance Computing Modernization Program  ‚Äì a computer program at the University of Central Florida.    #RepSotoDefenseApprops

I don‚Äôt just want to reduce veteran homelessness, I want to end it. In funding the Dept. of Veteran Affairs for next year, I requested an assessment on constructing single unit, tiny homes for rural homeless veterans and their families, an approach that could provide a pathway to stable housing for thousands. I also asked the VA to obtain more accurate data on at-risk veterans and report on actions taken to reduce homelessness in rural areas.    #RepSotoDefenseApprops

The Library of Congress provides invaluable services for us all. That's why for FY18 I secured funding to expand two of its community outreach programs: 1) increasing partnerships and fellowship opportunities with community colleges, HBCUs, and HSIs; and 2) continuing the Veterans History Project with increased participation from schools, Girl and Boy Scouts programs, and community stakeholders serving veterans from historically underrepresented groups to enhance the project.   #RepSotoDefenseApprops

To advance our nation's water security, I urged the Department of Defense to implement water conservation, reuse, and recharge practices on military installations. I also included an assessment report of coastal erosion and potential flooding risks in the proposed military construction projects.  #RepSotoDefenseApprops

I am committed to supporting our service members once they return home from the battlefield. That‚Äôs why I directed the VA to provide more effective treatment to combat-related post-traumatic stress disorder, by expanding Trauma Management Therapy. To help veterans transitioning into civilian life, I pushed for vocational agriculture programs and to assess the therapeutic benefits of farming, which could help treat the behavioral health conditions of veterans.  #RepSotoDefenseApprops

As a proud environmentalist, I prioritized energy efficiency and renewable energy projects when investing in our Department of Defense for FY18. I recommended over $285 million for solar energy programs at the Dept. of Energy, including expanding solar energy access to residences and businesses in low-income communities.   #RepSotoDefenseApprops

Although Zika is no longer an epidemic media spotlight, its dangers are still very real and will continue to affect us in central Florida. It is hard to believe it's been 16 years since the September 11th terror attacks on the American people. I remember this day like it was yesterday, sitting in a GW Law class just a few miles away from the Pentagon when it happened. Today, and every day, we remember the many lives lost on that tragic day ‚Äìone that will forever be ingrained in our hearts and minds. Reflecting on 9/11 and seeing the response in Florida as we face Irma, we're reminded of how brave and resilient America is when we stand together. Let's honor the heroic American men and women who risk their lives every day to keep our country safe! #NeverForget
